{
  "answer": "**In \"The Wife's Lament\" (chapter 3 of *Old English Elegies*), the speaker names her dwelling-place in the following passage from the translation:**\n\n> I was bid to dwell in a wooded grove,  \n> under an oak tree in this earth-cave.<sup>[1]</sup>\n\nThis corresponds precisely to lines 27–28 in the original Old English text:\n\n> Heht mec mon wunian  \n> on wuda bearwe,  \n> under actreo  \n> in þam eorðscræfe.<sup>[2]</sup>\n\nThe \"earth-cave\" (*eorðscræfe*) under the oak tree (*actreo*) in the wooded grove (*wuda bearwe*) is explicitly described here as her forced home.<sup>[3]</sup>\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 3 (*The Wife's Lament*), translation, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/#p-c1cc32).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 3 (*The Wife's Lament*), original, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/original/#p-eb2594).\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 3, [full chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/).",
